# Accessibility â€“ Frontend

Rules curated by **Spencer Goldade (spencergoldade.ca)**.

**Beginner-friendly** â€“ start here to make sure basic keyboard and screen-reader needs are covered.

Use this when working on frontend components or views that users interact with via mouse, touch, or keyboard.

**Relationship to other a11y guidance:** Principles (WCAG target, keyboard, semantics) are in `.cursor/rules/core/design-core.mdc`. This file defines frontend implementation. QA checklists that reference accessibility are in `.cursor/rules/binders/design-quality-testing.mdc`.

## Core Accessibility Targets

- Aim for **WCAG 2.1 AA or better** by default.
- Treat accessibility as a **first-class requirement**, not an optional enhancement.

## Structure and Semantics

- Use **semantic HTML** wherever possible (buttons for actions, links for navigation, headings for structure).
- Maintain a logical **heading hierarchy** (`h1` â†’ `h2` â†’ `h3`) that matches visual hierarchy.
- Use **landmarks** (for example, main, nav, header, footer) to help screen reader users navigate.

## ARIA and Interactive Elements

- Apply **ARIA roles, states, and properties** only when native semantics are insufficient.
- For any custom interactive component (for example, dropdowns, modals, tabs), ensure:
  - Correct role (for example, `role="dialog"`, `role="tablist"`).
  - **Keyboard interaction patterns** consistent with platform expectations.
  - Proper labeling via `aria-label`, `aria-labelledby`, or associated text.
- Provide **alt text** for informative images; mark decorative images as ignored by assistive tech.

## Focus and Keyboard Navigation

- Ensure that all interactive elements are reachable via keyboard **in a logical order**.
- Always provide a **visible focus state** that meets contrast requirements.
- Prevent and fix **keyboard traps**; users must be able to move into and out of components (especially dialogs) using standard keys.
- When opening modals or overlays:
  - Move focus into the modal.
  - Restore focus to a sensible element when the modal closes.

## Color and Contrast

- Use color tokens that maintain at least **AA-level contrast** for text and essential UI elements.
- Do not rely solely on color to communicate state (error, success, disabled); pair with icons or text.

## Anti-patterns

- Do **not** hide focus outlines without providing an accessible alternative.
- Do **not** implement custom components that only work with mouse or touch.
- Do **not** use ARIA to â€śpatchâ€ť semantics when a native element would accomplish the same goal more accessibly.

